    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>29<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Oct. 1855</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <date>7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Heshvan<add>?</add> 5615</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. I. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir.</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Your favor of<lb/>
                <date>3d. Heshvan</date> I duly received. It is true<lb/> that some remarks made by
                you<lb/> in conversation at the house of <persName>Mr Lyons</persName><lb/> on the
                night after <date>Kippur</date> have been<lb/> made the subject of conversation in<lb/>
                <placeName>New York</placeName>. Opinions so new &amp; startling<lb/> (however
                correct) from a teacher generally<lb/> considered so orthodox as the <persName>Revd
                    I Leeser</persName><lb/> were naturally discussed and commented<lb/> upon both
                by those who heard them<lb/> and those to whom they were repeated.<lb/> And now
                after reading your expla-<lb/>-nation of them, I am unable to</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>discover that the tongue of Slander<lb/> has been wagging—that the vile<lb/> &amp;
                malicious have been at work<lb/> or that mischief makers are among<lb/> us.</p>
            <p>You are quoted as having said<lb/> at <persName>Mr. Lyons</persName> (and to others) that<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">you</hi> would marry a <sic>christian</sic><lb/> girl having
                Jewish blood by<lb/> descent in the female line to any<lb/> Jew young man—this you
                do<lb/> not deny, but on the contrary<lb/> maintain to be good law by precept<lb/>
                and authority. I shall be<lb/> happy to lay your letter before<lb/> any who allude
                to the subject<lb/> to afford them the opportunity of<lb/> judging of the soundness
                of your<lb/> doctrines.</p>
            <p>with my best wishes for your<lb/> welfare I am dear sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Yours very respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">Benjn Nathan</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
